Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay Area. On June 28, 2017, the system officially launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company.

Ford GoBike, like other bike share systems, consists of a fleet of specially designed, sturdy and durable bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations throughout the city. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system, making them ideal for one-way trips. The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year and riders have access to all bikes in the network when they become a member or purchase a pass.

The Data Each trip is anonymized and includes:

Trip Duration (seconds)

Start Time and Date

End Time and Date

Start Station ID

Start Station Name

Start Station Latitude

Start Station Longitude

End Station ID

End Station Name

End Station Latitude

End Station Longitude

Bike ID

User Type (Subscriber or Customer – “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual)

Member Year of Birth

Member Gender

  • Duration_sec should be converted into minutes

  • User_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip can be converted to category

df_clean.start_time = pd.to_datetime(df_clean.start_time)

# change user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip to category

df_clean.member_gender = df_clean.member_gender.astype('category')

# change bike_id, start_station_id, end_station_id to object

In [35]:
#From start_time and end_time we can extract the  hour, date, day-weekdays & weekend

#create Hour for start and end
df_clean['start_time_hour']=df_clean['start_time'].dt.hour
df_clean['end_time_hour']=df_clean['end_time'].dt.hour

#Create Date column for start and end
df_clean['start_time_date'] = df_clean['start_time'].map(lambda x: x.strftime('%m-%d'))
df_clean['end_time_date'] = df_clean['end_time'].map(lambda x: x.strftime('%m-%d'))

#Create day-weekdays & weekend column for start and end
df_clean['start_time_weekday']=df_clean['start_time'].dt.strftime('%a')
df_clean['end_time_weekday']=df_clean['end_time'].dt.strftime('%a')

In [47]:
def rep(word):
    if word=='Male':
        return "Male"
    if word=='M':
        return "Male"
    if word=='Female':
        return "Female"
    if word=='F':
        return "Female"
    if word=='Other':
        return "Other"
    if word=='O':
        return "Other"
    if word=='?':
        return "Other"

Based on the above chart, it gives us clarity to see the trend of bike usage in day basis. The trend shows the volume of bike usage is reaching the peak point until Tuesday and start decrease towards weekend (Sunday). Overall, we can conclude that users are likely to use the bike during weekday rather weekend, this might due to people use it to commute to office and school. While during the weekend, people might use for recreational purposes.

def week_or_we(day):
    if day in ("Mon","Tue","Wed","Thu", "Fri"):
        return "Week_day"
    else:

Part 4: Requirement of Bike Replenishment During The Peak Hours¶

For bike replenishment analysis, we only interested in two peak hours periods which are Morning from 7-9 a.m and Afternoon from 4-7 p.m . Each data set will be created for each peak hour periods and followed by calculating the difference in each station by substracting number of bike is leaving (start_station_name) and bike is ariving (end_station_name).

Any negative number indicates the stations is shortage in bike, while the positive number indicates excessive bike.

#Morning peak hours: 7-9 a.m
#Counting the difference from the bike being taken and bike being return from start station and end station
leaving=df_peak_morning.groupby('start_station_name').size().rename('leaving_bike_count').to_frame()
arriving=df_peak_morning.groupby('end_station_name').size().rename('arriving_bike_count').to_frame()
mor_bike_count=arriving.merge(leaving, left_index=True, right_index=True)
mor_bike_count['difference']=mor_bike_count.leaving_bike_count-mor_bike_count.arriving_bike_count

Summary¶

Based on the above analysis, here are the summary and recommendation:

Part 1: Bike Usage Analysis Based on Time¶

  • Daily Bike Usage in June 2019 is shown as multimodal distribution where the peak bike usage volume is dominated by weekday
  • The trend shows the volume of bike usage is reaching the peak point until Tuesday and start decrease towards weekend (Sunday). Overall, we can conclude that users are likely to use the bike during weekday rather weekend, this might due to people use it to commute to office and school. While during the weekend, people might use for recreational purposes.
  • The peak hours of bike usage can be divided into two period, such as Morning peak-hours and Afternoon peak-hours which are from 7-9a.m and 4-7p.m respectively. This might due to people commute from house to office or school in the morning and inversely during the afternoon.
  • By calculating the percentage of trips instead of bike count, it will show a good comparison between bike usage between weekday and weekend. Otherwise, the chart for weekend always be lower since the number of bike usage on weekday is accumulated by 5 days of bike usage. By comparing this two data, it can tell us that there is no significant difference between trip length during weekday and weekend. A slight difference only can be found where trip length in weekend is slightly lower in general, this might due to less congestion during the weekend.

  • Based on the gender distribution, Male is dominating the bike usage by having more than 70% of population and followed by Female for more than 20%, and the rest belongs to other.

In general, number of bike usage trend based on daily is decreasing from Wednesday towards weekend and it applies to all age.
  • Based on the above bivariate explotation, number of males user are decreasing sharply from Wednesday towards weekend, while female and other gender user decrease gradually
  • Based on the above multivariate exploration, Male and Female user gender are having similar trend based on the member age where it is dominated by user with 20-30 years old and followed by 30-40 years old user for the whole of week. (Note: Due to the large bike shortage number in San Francisco Caltrain Station 2, the prioritization of bike replenishment is only made in those 3 stations by considering the balance of bike excessive and shortage)

Limitation¶

  1. Distance between station to another station is not investigated in this project since it requeries further study about San Fransisco Map. Therefore, the data about longitude and latitude was dropped since it is not relevant to this project
  2. Further mapping studies are also required to optimize the bike replenishment recommendation by considering distance from 1 station to another station and also congestion data would be an important information.
